First time hanging real garland and I learned a few things! I opted for soft foam wire instead of all the suggestions I saw on IG. Command strips and I have a love hate and can do a number on your wood! And zip ties and floral wire can really damage your banister too. This foam wire was cheap and super easy to use-like tying a bag of bread haha. And then give me alll of the real garland because my home smells SO good!!! I float down the stairs to the smell of pine, cedar and fir!!! Not sure how long it will last but I would give it 2 weeks at it’s prime so I wouldn’t hang real garland day after Thanksgiving and expect it to be popping for your Christmas dinner. I chose real garland this year cause it’s also wayyyy more affordable than the faux stuff. Gotta wait for a sale for that. I would be spending hundreds instead of $40-$50 for my entire staircase! Grabbed mine from @homedepot ! For accents I tied some maroon ribbon —duh (@taylorswift) and called it a day! I LOVE how it turned out!!! Spray it with water every day to every other day to help make it last longer. Let me know if you have any questions!

Christmas Tree Sugar Cookies 
By Brandi Milloy 

Ingredients 
2 and 1/4 cups all-purpose flour
1/2 teaspoon baking powder
1/4 teaspoon salt
3/4 cup unsalted butter, room temperature 
3/4 cup granulated sugar
1 large egg, at room temperature
3 teaspoons pure vanilla extract
Green gel food coloring 
Black gel food coloring
Powdered sugar 
Almond extract 

Directions 
Mix flour, baking powder and salt. Set aside. 

Using a hand mixer, mix butter and sugar together. Add egg, vanilla and food coloring a little at a time. 

Combine dry and wet ingredients and mix together until dough forms. Onto a clean, floured surface roll dough until 1/4” thick. Cut out trees or desired shape and place on baking sheet. Put in freezer for 5-10 min so dough keeps shape while baking. 

Bake at 350F for 10-13 min being sure not to over bake!  Let cool. 

Make frosting by mixing 2 cups powdered sugar with 4 tbsp. water or milk depending on consistency you’d like. Add 1/2 tsp. almond extract and mix. Drizzle on cooled cookies and top with sprinkles while wet!

Drinking chocolate ain’t hot cocoa. It’s the French Hot Chocolate, it’s the perfect drink at the North Pole, it’s Judy’s specialty!!! I fell in love with drinking chocolate when I lived in Europe but now I get my fix in my own kitchen. There’s something so special about it, so I only make it in December. Some recipes taste like you’re literally drinking a melted chocolate bar and that is totally fine, but I found the perfect consistency without being too heavy. Also, this is one of my favorite holiday movies ever. What is yours?

Drinking Chocolate
By @BrandiMilloy

1 cup whole milk
3/4 cup high quality chocolate (chopped or morsels)
1/4 tsp. Vanilla extract
Pinch of salt

Directions
Heat your milk over medium heat on the stove top until warm and bubbles form around the sides.  Add your chocolate and stir until melted. Remove from heat and let it cool slightly. Serve immediately, or pour into a shaker and shake. But fair warning: if the liquid is too warm, you won’t be able to shake it.

Oreo mint bark is hands-down, one of my most requested treats I make every season. It’s super simple to make and way better than the crushed up candy cane version. The crunchy @oreo cookie with the cream @guittardchocolate mint morsels and dark chocolate drizzle is so good you’ll want to make a few batches for yourself! This is also a good one to whip up for your neighbors to bring some holiday cheer!

Mint Oreo Bark
By @brandimilloy 

Melt 1 bag @guittardchocolate mint morsels in the microwave for 30 seconds at a time until soft. Mix until smooth being careful not to burn. Spread onto parchment lined baking sheet. Top with half a bag of chopped Oreos. Melt half a bag of milk or dark chocolate and drizzle on top of bark. Place in freezer for 15 minutes to harden and set up. Break apart and enjoy! Keep in fridge or freezer. The best!!!!

This is one of the most clutch things you need to learn how to make. Candied citrus can elevate any dish, charcuterie board or drink. Dip it in chocolate and add some flaky sea salt and it is out of this world. It’s prime citrus season so head to your grocery store to pick up dozens of handpicked @sunkistcitrus varieties like blood oranges, Cara Cara and lemons! I can’t stop eating these!!!🍊
Chocolate Dipped Candied Citrus
By @brandimilloy
Slice 3 blood oranges in 1/4” slices. Add 3 cups of water to a large stock pot. Add 1.5 cups of sugar. Heat on medium high until sugar melts and small boil begins. Add sliced oranges and lower temperature to medium low and cook for about an hour continuing to stir and flipping oranges over. Remove oranges from sugar water and place on wire rack. Dry for at least 24 hours, flipping over halfway. Roll in sugar and enjoy or dip in chocolate and sprinkle tops with flaky sea salt. Place in refrigerator to set up. Store in lided container on counter for up to 5 days to maintain freshness.

If you want to be the most popular person at the party BRING THESE. End of story. They can convert even the most stubborn who think they don’t like marshmallow cereal treats. These are salty, sweet, soft and chewy. The perfect amount of cereal to marshmallow do buttery goodness ratio! You can’t stop at just one. It’s a problem. I love these so much and the amount of compliments I get every time I make them is worth it alone. Let me know what you think when you try them!
🥰
Best Damn Salty Sweet Rice Krispie Treats
By @brandimilloy

Ingredients 
1 cup butter, cubed 
2 10oz bags mini marshmallows
A few pinches of salt 
10 cups rice cereal

Directions 
1. Line a 9x13” dish with parchment paper. 
2. In a large stock pot melt your butter on medium low. This is going to take a minute so don’t rush it. Once your butter melts it will start to foam. Stir to prevent burning as brown butter starts to form. Once your butter becomes tan and you see little flecks turn your heat to lowest setting and add your marshmallows. Stir to combine. Add your salt and stir. 
3. Once your marshmallows are melted remove from heat and add your cereal, folding it in a few cups at a time. 
4. Pour mixture into dish and gently press to fill. Allow to cool for a few minutes before cutting into squares. Enjoy!!!

Figuring out what to do with all of your children’s artwork and paperwork they bring home from school can get overwhelming. This system has worked really well for us. It basically breaks down to this: display, keep or recycle and preserve. I know there are plenty of solutions out there where companies will scan your child’s artwork and put it into a bound book but to me, there is nothing more special than having the actual piece of work…feeling the craft and the glue and stickers, the smudge of the pastels and texture of the finger paint. I was also surprised how little I held onto once I really had to decide what would go in the binder. Last school year I only kept about 10 pieces of art which fit into five page protectors. Before I put everything away I also make sure to add the date on the back. What other tips do you have when it comes to organizing your child’s artwork? Oreo Dip
By @brandimilloy

1/2 cup butter
1/3 cup brown sugar
8 ounces cream cheese
1/2 cup powdered sugar
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
Pinch of salt
3/4 cup Oreos, crushed

Directions

2. And a larger bowl, cream together your cream cheese and powdered sugar, add vanilla extract, salt, and then slowly add your butter and brown sugar mixture. Fold in your Oreos.

Jalapeño Popper Dip
By @brandimilloy

1/2 cup roasted red peppers, chopped

1 cup cottage cheese
1/2 tsp. onion powder
Salt & pepper

Three things we always do every night at supper time:

Start our meal with Grace. Most days my 3 year old son likes to lead us in prayer. 

My five-year-old daughter started a gratitude circle where she begins by saying something she is grateful for or something or someone she is praying for.  She does this in school with her teacher and classmates and brought the practice to our home. 

Then we take turns asking one another “what was something kind you did today?” I love hearing these answers the most. 

And even though our children are young, no one leaves the table until they are excused. Sometimes this leads to playing a card game together before even putting the dishes away. Other times we have a family meeting and go over everyone’s schedule for the following day. And then often times they go play and Mom & Dad get to have quiet time together. 

We started eating dinner by candle light because I had this idea that I would tell the kids that if they stayed at the table even after they were done eating or done not eating (it happens!) that they could blow out the candle. So now they each have one. And they still love it every time!

Loaded Bean Dip that hits!!! I got my hands on some @rancho_gordo #pintobeans and knew I had to make this. Although these are not just any pinto beans, they are heirloom beans that are considered Gold by Chef Thomas Keller so perhaps a dip shouldn’t have been the first thing I thought of since these beans are so so special!!! Pinto means “painted” and these are like beams of art! Like nothing you have ever had before. So creamy and flavorful. Cheesy, creamy, slightly spicy, this dip is the perfect after school snack for Mom!!! Seriously, I’m a bean dip and chip gal, never hummus and celery. You could totally make this recipe with a can of your favorite refried beans, but there is nothing like making them from scratch! This recipe requires no soaking and if you want to make it real simple you could do all of this in the slow cooker. Just DM me for a few modifications. I call this a dip but you can just eat these with a spoon like you would traditional refried beans.

Loaded Bean Dip
By @brandimilloy

8oz dried pinto beans, rinsed 
Water
1/2 block cream cheese
1 can diced tomatoes & chilis
1/2 tbsp. Ground cumin
1/2 tbsp. Onion salt
1 jalapeño, diced (remove seeds for mild flavor)
1 cup shredded Monterey Jack cheese
1 cup shredded white cheddar cheese
Garnish: sliced Cherry tomatoes, jalapeño, more cheese and cilantro!
Directions 
1. Place beans in large pot and cover with 2 inches of water. Bring to a boil for 10 to 15 minutes and then set heat to low and cover. Allow to simmer for 1 to 2 hours until beans are super soft and water is absorbed.
2. Smash beans until creamy and add remaining ingredients. Stir to combine and garnish. Enjoy alone or with chips as a dip!

It might be the only gift they’ve ever received. ✨ I’m so grateful to help hand out Boxes of Joy with @crosscatholic in the Dominican Republic this week. Milly’s school participates in this program so it was a real full circle moment to be there and watch a little boy discover a few of the exact same things we packed in our box.

🎁 Box of Joy is a shoebox that is donated and packed with toys, clothing, school supplies and other essential items by U.S. parishes, schools and groups. They go to some of the poorest communities in the world. These boxes are powerful. I watched as children opened their box and savored every item, examining each part of it. The newness of a pair of pajamas, the way a brand new doll smells, a bright blue toothbrush, the way an orange matchbox car shines, how soft a new lovey feels, their very own set of sharp colorful crayons. These boxes give hope. They remind these children they are loved and prayed over. They create memorable experiences. Many of the children wanted to wait until they were home to open their box—too scared it wasn’t real and it would be taken away. I followed one little boy home where he happily shared his box with his six siblings. They are tremendously grateful. Every single thing is desired and adored. 
🙏🏽
Anyone can participate in this program. I’ve learned that most people are hungry to help. They just need the encouragement and invitation. Here’s yours:

💻 Send an evite to all your friends inviting them to fill a box of joy and then let them know when they should come over & drop them off. 

💖 Rally your neighborhood, soccer club, Pilates gym, all the stylists at your hair salon, your book club, grief support group, alumni, your coworkers, etc to create a group to give boxes of joy together!

👩‍👧 Make it a Mommy & Me day where you all shop & pack with your children together.

🎉 For you or your child’s birthday this year request guests fill a box of joy in lieu of gifts.

Go to CrossCatholic.org/boxofjoy to get all of the deets and a kit to get your started. You can also make a donation to gift a box put together by the outreach team.

Stuffed shells just like my mom would make. How many of you love this dish as much as I do? It is so simple to put together no excuses! On Wednesdays we typically have some type of pasta dish and this one has been on rotation since I went to the Dominican Republic and made a batch in the freezer for Mr. A and the babies to enjoy while I was gone. I kind of forgot how delicious it is!!!
Stuffed Shells
By @brandimilloy
30 pasta shells
1-32oz. container ricotta cheese
2 cups shredded mozzarella cheese
1 cup grated parmesan cheese 
1 cup grated pecorino Romano cheese
2 eggs 
1 tbsp. Italian dried herbs
1/2 tsp. grated nutmeg (optional)
1 tsp. Salt
1 tsp. Pepper
Zest of 1 lemon 
1- 28oz. jar pasta sauce

Directions
Preheat oven to 350°. Meanwhile, boil your pasta shells for about 10 minutes until they are al dente. Strain and set aside.
To make the filling, add your ricotta to a large bowl. Add half of all of the cheeses, eggs, spices and lemon zest. Mix!
Into a casserole dish, pour a few tablespoons of pasta sauce to coat the bottom. Start filling your shelves with the ricotta mixture and placing them in the casserole dish. Layer with half of the remaining cheeses and half of your pasta sauce. Stuff the remaining shells and top with the leftover pasta sauce and whatever cheese you have left. Bake for 30 minutes or until your dish is bubbly and warm all the way through! If you’re freezing it for later just cover to make airtight and write the date on it so you know when you made it. To serve, remove from the freezer in the morning and place in fridge. When you’re ready to bake, bake as directed, but it may take 35-45 minutes.

Garlic Butter Shrimp
By @brandimilloy

Ingredients
Avocado oil
4 tbsp. Butter 
1 lb. shrimp, thawed (shells & tails removed, optional)
1/2 cup. Cornstarch
Salt and pepper
5 garlic cloves, crushed
1 bottle @eatshrimpdaddy garlic butter sauce

Directions 
1. Heat a wok on medium high heat. Add a few tablespoons of avocado oil and 2tbsp of butter. Blot your shrimp dry. Add cornstarch to a shallow bowl and season with a pinch of salt and pepper. Take a tour with me of our @airbnb in Lake Como, Italy! This place was such a magical find. We loved the location. It was actually located in a town called Torno, which is close to the town of Como but so much cuter and more quaint. The listing was brand new to Airbnb so I’m pretty sure we were the first ones to stay there. I typically avoid new listings since there are no previous reviews but the host owns over 100 places with amazing reviews. The location overlooked Lake Como, the Marina in Torno, with three restaurants downstairs, and a coffee shop within walking distance. We had cars for visiting the area, but the marina downstairs had water taxis and a ferry you could take to the other cities in Lake Como. The place slept six with two big bedrooms with queen size+ beds and a pull out couch in the living room. The place was clean and had minimal decor with some really great artwork. It felt new like they had just finished renovating it. Finding a place that was pet friendly was key, and this place did not charge more for us to bring our friend’s two doggies. Most importantly, we really wanted to find a place that had air conditioning since a lot of places do not have it. We visited Italy during a heat wave in the middle of summer, so having the air conditioning when we got home was so refreshing and made it so easy to be comfortable and sleep well. We made use of their washer and did laundry. Since most places in Europe do not have dryers, we did it on the first day so that our clothes had plenty of time to air dry. The kitchen was fully stocked with everything you would need to cook at home, but we ate out enjoying local cuisine. The price was extremely fair for the area (and otherwise) and came out to around $400/night. Drop a note below if you’d like the link or have any questions!

Here’s how you make them: Grab a tube of refrigerated biscuit dough and roll each biscuit until you can cut each one into 4 pieces. Fill a pot with water and when it comes to a boil, add a quarter cup of baking soda. Carefully drop your biscuit pieces into the water and boil for about 15 seconds on each side. Spray a cooking sheet with avocado oil and lay your pretzel bites on the pan. You can brush them when egg wash if you would like but definitely sprinkle them with flaky sea salt. Bake at 425° for 13 minutes. While they are baking, make the easiest beer cheese dip ever. Pour about a cup of your favorite beer into a pot. I grabbed a @santamonicabrewworks 310 Blonde. He’s a beer on a medium high heat until it starts to bubbles and then add half a block of cream cheese about 4 ounces. Whisk that together until it is completely melted and then lower your heat too low. Add a cup and a half of sharp cheddar cheese and a cup and a half of pepper, jack cheese, and stir until combined.  If you were having trouble getting your sauce to thicken up, add a teaspoon of cornstarch adding a half a teaspoon at a time.

Once your pretzels are done baking, serve them immediately nice and warm with that delicious beer cheese dip!!! These are a great weekend treat but especially good on game day. What is your favorite thing to make during football season? Let me know below ⬇️.

A hack for figuring out dinner every night of the week!!! We’ve been following this format for years and years and it keeps the mundane question of what are we eating or what should we make for dinner obsolete. This schedule has really been so helpful and has worked for us without feeling repetitive. Feel free to come up with your own but once you commit to a theme each night, you’ll be so grateful you’re no longer wasting time figuring out what to have or what to buy. Here’s our schedule:
Monday- meatless Monday. Usually we enjoy some type of fish, starch and vegetable. But during these cold-weather months, you could make Mondays your soup day and have potato cheese soup and a salad (for example!)
Tuesdays- we always celebrate taco Tuesdays and even play mariachi music while we cook. We love Mexican food, so this is a win-win every single week. Some weeks we will make big bowls with rice, protein, lettuce, and all the Fixin’s. Other weeks we will enjoy shrimp tacos, or keep it simple and have loaded quesadillas.
Wednesday-we always enjoy pasta on Wednesdays. My favorite is when Mr. A makes homemade pasta with pink sauce and we enjoy a big salad on the side. My children love to eat salad, especially when I have their favorite Caesar dressing and lots of crunchy toppings.
Thursday- usually we enjoy some type of Asian cuisine like a stirfry using leftovers from the fridge. We also love these veggie spring rolls and shrimp tempura we get from Costco. Add it to some steamed white rice and there’s dinner!!! But Thurs is kind of wild card for us. There are definitely weeks where we go to In-N-Out.
Friday- we have pizza every single Friday. Over the years Mr. A has perfected his homemade pizza dough recipe along with all the homemade sauces. We love hosting friends, but we definitely enjoy pizza Friday just us four often. It’s a time honored tradition we cherish so much and when we hope our children will remember fondly.
on the weekends, we usually indulge and order sushi or go to our favorite restaurant, but we really try to be conscious of the food we have at the house. For example, most Sundays after church we head home and enjoy leftover pizzas from Friday night!

1 week before Christmas two years ago my parents ate a late breakfast, called to see how my daughter’s first dance recital went, my Dad made a joke to my Mom and then moments later his heart stopped and he died. That time in my life is a blur. It’s the most excruciating pain I’ve ever felt. It’s awful and gut wrenching when you lose someone you love. He was our world, my person, a friend I talked to sometimes several times a day. And nothing will ever be the same no matter how much time passes. You can barely function when someone you love dies, the world feels so cruel and nothing makes sense. It’s dark and lonely and during all of the pain there is so much to do. It’s overwhelming trying to even function. But after my world felt like it ended there are things people did that made it feel less lonely. These gestures made all the difference and are acts of kindness during that time that I cherish in the deepest part of my heart.

Here’s what to do when someone you know loses someone they love—

•Be there. Just be there. Go there. Physically be there with them and if you can’t physically be there, virtually be there for them. Call them as soon as possible. Call them again. Leave a voicemail. An old friend called me 3 times before I had enough in me to answer. A simple text saying “I’m here for you. I’m available to talk when you’re ready. You don’t have to say anything but I’m here to listen” makes all the difference in making sure that person doesn’t feel alone in their pain.

•Bring them food, send them food or send a food delivery/restaurant gift card. People who are grieving can barely function. Feeding them is one less thing they need to figure out. Send nourishing food that sustains and warms the soul like soups, pasta, salad. Do not send a cake. Do not send chocolate covered strawberries. Both things I received that are food I associate with celebratory occasions and felt very confusing and tone deaf.

Grief is all consuming. And it’s different for everyone- but if you care, don’t give up on them and keep checking in to let them know you’re there. Sometimes a walk together outside is all the heart is ready for. Let me know if you’d like to hear more ⬇️

When my Dad died I felt so betrayed. By him, by my family, by God. There were a lot of emotions but mostly I just didn’t feel like it was his time. My instincts and faith and pure gut feeling told me that day wouldn’t be the day God called him Home…and yet on a Saturday afternoon in the middle of traffic when I still had 7 more hours of driving my sister called and said he was gone. And there was nothing I could do. Nothing felt real. My world didn’t make sense. It’s like you’re sinking into mud and you can’t move but you also have no energy to try. It’s despair and hopelessness and your brain can’t wrap your head around what just happened. 

When you lose someone you deeply love you don’t just lose them once. You lose them over and over again. The permanence of death is so final. It’s awful and painful like if every bone in your body broke. The simple act of breathing took energy.

It felt like nothing was as it seemed and even when I would look at a sunset or the ocean, which used to be my favorite thing in the world—it looked like nothingness. It looked like a lie.

It took me about a year of committing to a routine of healing for the ocean to look beautiful again. It took time and a lot of hard work and I dove into anything I could do to help me get on the other side of it. And by other side of it I just mean to a place where you can function and see the light again. If you’re grieving, missing, longing I just want you to know you are not alone. Grief is all the massive amounts of love you have for them with no where to go.  All you need to focus on is getting through each day one day at a time. When someone you love dies, you realize real quick just how much we take for granted. Each day. Each breath. Each season. Each year. But death can happen in an instant. We all think we’ll die when we’re old, ideally in our sleep. After we’ve lived a full life and are content in bed. But in reality people die driving home from work, while they’re walking their dog or after long battles with illnesses that have stripped them of any quality of life anyway. Death comes whenever it wants stealing time and joy away and leaving a path of destruction and heartbreak. There are no second chances. So how can we ensure we are actually living life when we are living? Practicing introspection/self examination and re-evaluating your priorities, habits and how you’re spending your time is a good start. 

So stop what you’re doing and ask yourself these questions before you die:

What do you love doing that you don’t do enough?
Who are your mentors? 
What are your favorite memories?
What lights you up?
What feeds your soul?
If you could write a goodbye/last day on Earth letter what would it say?
What are you proud of?
What is something on your bucket list and how do you plan on doing it?
How did you show up for your family or friends this year?
Have you given back to your community? To others?
What are your hopes & dreams?
How would your best friend describe you?
What obstacles have you overcome?
What does your obituary say about you?
What do you want to be remembered by?
.

The hardest part of death? Besides the ginormous hole they leave in the world? The permanence. The forever. The finality of it all. It’s over and can feel unbearable, unbelievable. The expectations and plans, the picture you had drawn over and over again in your mind, the milestones missed, how the daily habits that revolved around the person just stops, the vacations that won’t happen.

The five stages of grief are – denial, anger, bargaining, depression and acceptance – often talked about as if they happen in order, moving from one stage to the other. I would add that there’s a stage of defeat —when you are just so exhausted by all of it and want to give up. I remember having to call my Dad’s retirement fund or something and send the death certificate and the guy on the other line was so matter of fact asking me questions like his “death date.” I couldn’t stomach saying that date one more time and I just started crying on the phone telling him that the person that died was my Dad and he meant everything to me. I asked if he could please consider that this is the last thing I wanted to do and something I tried to take on to avoid having my mom do one more awful tedious thing. He didn’t say anything and then I realized he felt really awful and he immediately apologized. The first thing that popped into my head was how I would typically call my Dad to tell him what happened. I told him everything. I would call him on my way to work, walking through the grocery store, to tell him a funny story, about a new coffee, to get his advice on a business decision…he was the best listener and always direct with his opinions. When he died the music died. Death is final. There’s no undoing it, or going back or negotiating. Unlike anything else in the world once the door is closed it’s shut. It’s the most powerless position. That’s the hardest part. 

My heart goes out to anyone who is feeling sad, defeated, powerless, missing someone who has gone before us. I pray you can find comfort in the memories you have with them, that they visit you in your dreams and you feel their presence all around you. Ask them for a sign you can’t miss. I believe we will be together again.

After my Dad died suddenly and my world felt so wrong I committed to grief therapy within a few months. Not because I felt like it would fix anything but because the magnitude of his passing was so tremendous I knew that I needed a professional to help me. The stars aligned on the program I chose and who I ended up matching with and I’m forever grateful to the team of people who reached out to me and gave me a life vest when I was drowning.

During my 16 week program one of the tasks I was given was to write a letter to my Dad.  Just write a letter. Put pen to paper and just start. And when you think you have nothing left to say keep writing. This is a letter just for you and that person, no one else.  A few weeks or a month later my therapist had my write another letter. But this time I wrote a letter from my Dad to me. 

You might think you don’t know what to say but I believe the person who you are writing to will help you write the letters. Maybe go somewhere that was special to you both, or enjoy a beverage you both enjoyed, play the music your souls loved and just write. I hope you try this. Do it for them. And then pass this on to someone else. I’m holding space for you.

The first thing my therapist asked me to commit to when my world was wrecked upside down by the death of my Dad was creating a morning routine for myself. When you’re feeling overwhelmed and out of control, routine can bring certainty, structure and order to the chaos of grief. Small, manageable choices can start a positive ripple effect. 

Here are the 3 things my routine needed to include:

🏃🏽‍♀️Movement | (Ideally this is done as soon as soon you wake up.) I decided my movement would be a brisk walk, sometimes with friends (accountability partners are great), but mostly solo. Moving my body once a day proved to be a great stress reliever and I knew that if I kept putting one foot in front of the other it meant I was still here. I also know that the body stores emotions, trauma and grief and that moving my body would help release all that sadness and ease the pain. 

🌅 Mother Nature | I’ve always felt a strong connection to nature but knowing the powerful effects of nature on my body like reducing cortisol levels, improving mood and lowering stress helped me take getting outdoors seriously. I tried to do grounding as much as I could which is when you touch your body to the ground (like walking barefoot in the grass or sand, running your hand along a plant or gardening) and the idea is that Earth carries a negative charge and when we make a physical connection with the earth, through grounding, we discharge excess energy, which in turn is said to have a healing effect at a cellular level. Regardless of what you believe being outside under the sun and getting fresh air will always make you feel better.

🧘🏽‍♀️ Meditation | I have never been into meditation or invested time into learning how to meditate. It’s not my thing and I felt like I didn’t really get it. But when my therapist told me this was one of the best ways to connect with my Dad I committed. At first he would walk me through a guided meditation then I started doing it on my own, sitting in silence and breathing in for 4 seconds, holding the breath for 7 seconds, and exhaling for 8 seconds. After my Dad died suddenly some of my most treasured moments were when people would tell me stories about him or share the reasons why he was great. Someone told me “the best way to honor your Dad is to be all of his great qualities, be more like him.” My dad, who I called BDawg was the kind of guy who would make friends with his mechanic, he would let the person behind him cut in line just cause. Growing up, he left us all notes on our bathroom mirror with words of affirmation and encouragement. My Dad would sit at the dinner table helping me for hours while I cried about how hard math homework was. When he met you he would want to know your story, he would ask questions and then listen attentively. He always rooted for the underdog, in life, in sports. He wouldn’t order food at restaurants cause he knew we wouldn’t finish ours and wasting food was one of the worst things you could do-it meant you had no regard for money, the people who prepared the food, the truck drivers who make the world go round and the farmers that grew it all. He always gave to the poor but not just change in their can or money in the offering at church—he would invite homeless to eat lunch with him. He’d ask them to sit with him, he’d give them food, respect and company. I wrote a list of traits my Dad was really great at and I keep them posted to look at. There are so many ways you can honor someone who has died. Here is a list I came up with:

•Support causes they loved (volunteer/advocate)
•Spend time talking to them or about them
•Share their legacy, write down stories about them
•Eat their favorite foods, listen to their favorite music
•Continue traditions that were important to them
•Create a photo album/memory book
•Finish projects they didn’t get to complete
•Plant a tree or flower, garden
•Try your loved one’s hobby or learn a new skill they were good at
•Complete a personal goal they encouraged you to do
•Repurpose their items like turning their tshirts into a quilt
•Frame a note/quote from them, or a recipe
•Travel to a spot that was special to them
•Fund a scholarship in their memory
•Celebrate their life every year
